bug.short_desc: IE has issues with loading PNG images without the AlphaImageLoader

long_desc.thetext:
Stefan Volbers reported via mailinglist this issue in IE7. This is an issue which was originally reported by Maria Siebert right before the 0.8 release.
The fix for this issue was reverted two weeks ago because we thought this one is not necessary anymore. But it seems that this fix is still necessary to apply.
Thanks to Stefan Volbers for reporting and Dominik Horb for confirming this one.
Created attachment 681 Screenshot showing PNG image issues in IE7

Applied fix with Revision #21214.
Keeping this bug as reminder to check for at next releases (with lower priority and severity). Moving on to milestone 1.1 and back to my pool.

This reason for this issue is a dual-monitor setup. We have to decide if we can live with this issue and disable the AlphaImageLoader or to use the AlphaImageLoader and live with the performance issues.
To our knowledge this is a very rare visual issue that also only shows up in a dual-monitor setup (IE and/or graphics driver related), so lets keep the performance benefits and not use AIL.

Unfortunately we still have to keep the support for AIL. The reason is the lacking support of IE (7 and 8) for CSS opacity for alpha PNGs. Currently we use an alpha opacity filter to set the opacity for images. Setting this filter for an alpha PNG results in a badly rendered image. A possible solution would be to replace images (already supported with the "-disabled" suffix) whenever the "enabled" property is set to "false".
On top of this IE8 is suffering from performance issues with decorators if AIL is disabled (Bug #2185).
Moving on to 1.3 to think over if we plan to provide "-disabled" images for every icon of the framework and to add tool-chain support so the application developers can easily add their own "-disabled" images to their application.
As this would mean the user would have to supply a disabled image too, we just stick with the AlphaImageLoader and hope that IE9 will make the world a better place!
